<F P=100> EAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Narcotics Roundup for 23-29 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Narcotics Roundup for 23-29 May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK3105153594 </F>
<F P=103> BK3105153594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on narcotics developments in South Asia, Southeast Asia, 
and the Pacific monitored by Bangkok Bureau between 23 and 29 
May 1994. Source information is given in parentheses after each 
item. 
<H5>  SOUTH ASIA </H5>
<H5>  India </H5>
<H5>  Officials Seize Heroin in Lucknow Raid </H5>
  Officials of the Central Bureau of Narcotics seized 775 
grams 
of heroin in a raid conducted on the Aliganj, Lucknow residence 
of two "notorious smugglers" identified as Ms. Afsha and Ms. 
Hazrabegum. (Delhi THE HINDUSTAN TIMES in English 21 May 94 p 9) 
<H5>  Pakistan </H5>
<H5>  Nine Arrested in Lahore With Heroin, Opium </H5>
  Nine people have been arrested by the Antinarcotics Task 
Force in Lahore after they were found with 45 kg of heroin, 100 
liters of acetic anhydride, and 108 kg of opium. Eight of the 
suspects were identified as Ghafoor Niazi, Ijaz Ahmed Khalid, 
Shoukat Ali, Altaf, Rafique, Jamshed, Arshad, and Azhar Butt. 
(Karachi DAWN in English 21 May 94 p 6) 
<H5>  Frontier Corps Seizes Opium Bound for Iran </H5>
  The Frontier Corps recovered 80 kg of fine opium in the Mand 
area as it was being smuggled to Iran by camel. There were no 
arrests. (Islamabad THE NATION in English 26 May 94 p 12) 
<H5>  SOUTHEAST ASIA </H5>
<H5>  Burma </H5>
<H5>  Authorities Kill Two, Arrest Six, Seize 23 Kg of Heroin </H5>
  Acting on a tip, members of the Defense Services 
Intelligence 
Unit and the antiterrorist group of Mong Ko-Phaungsai Region 
stopped a group of people near Namtaung Village, Mu-se Township 
on 8 May. One of the suspects threw a grenade; the authorities 
returned small arms fire. Yi Sein, 20, and an unidentified 
suspect were killed in the exchange. Six others were seized 
along with 90 packets of heroin weighing 23.08 kg: Kyan Pi San, 
18; Mo Tae Chan, 20; Kyaw Lwin, alias Wan Min Khwan, 20; Kyin 
San, 25; Mar Dut, 28; and Aik Gnaw, 26. (Rangoon THE NEW LIGHT 
OF BURMA in English 14 May 94 p 7) 
<H5>  Authorities Seize Heroin, Arrest Three in Shwepyithar </H5>
  Members of the Rangoon special antidrug squad and 
Shwepyithar 
police searched the house of U San Myint, 40, and Daw Cho Cho, 
32, in Zigon Ward, Shwepyithar on 6 May. They found 27.155 
grams of heroin in plastic containers hidden under a pile of 
humus in a hut. The authorities also arrested Daw Cho Cho's 
brother Kyi Win, 29. (Rangoon THE NEW LIGHT OF BURMA in English 
19 May 94 p 7) 
<H5>  Mandalay Railway Police Seize Opium </H5>
  On 20 April, the Mandalay Railway Police seized 6.367 kg of 
opium from Myint Kyaw, 25, a passenger on the Mandalay-Myitkyina 
train. (Rangoon THE NEW LIGHT OF BURMA in English 19 May 94 p 7) 
<H5>  Opium Seized in Mogaung Township; Two Arrested </H5>
  Acting on a tip, a combined group from the Defense Services 
Intelligence Unit, Namti People's Police Force, and the ward law 
and order restoration council searched the house of Ma N Khun 
Taung, 35, in Namti Village, Mogaung Township on 3 May. They 
found 3.918 kg of opium. They also arrested Ma Rit Kaw Jah, 32, 
the owner of the drugs. (Rangoon THE NEW LIGHT OF BURMA in 
English 24 May 94 p 7) 
<H5>  Laos </H5>
<H5>  Provincial Court Imprisons Woman on Opium Charge </H5>
  On 25 May, the Sayaboury Province People's Court sentenced 
Ms. Teng, 37, of Nakha village, Boten District to six months and 
15 days in jail and fined her 70,000 kip. She was charged with 
possession of 43 kg of opium. The court proceedings, 
interrogation, and police investigation showed that the accused 
did not intend to violate state laws. The opium was 
subsequently destroyed by the authorities. (Vientiane Vitthayou 
Hengsat Radio Network in Lao 0000 GMT 27 May 94) 
<H5>  Philippines </H5>
<H5>  Narcotics Agents Arrest 25, Seize Methamphetamine </H5>
Hydrochloride 
  Narcotics Command agents have confiscated 20.484 kg of 
methamphetamine hydrochloride worth 51 million pesos from 25 
drug dealers during a week-long operation. Among those arrested 
were two members of the Police Aviation Security Command 
assigned to Ninoy Aquino International Airport, a police 
officer, the son of a police officer, and two overseas 
Filipinos. (Quezon City GMA-7 Radio- Television Arts Network in 
Tagalog 0930 GMT 23 May 94) 
<H5>  Narcotics Regional Command Destroys Marijuana in Sulu </H5>
  Elements of the 9th Narcotics Regional Command destroyed 
some 
65,000 marijuana plants, 15,000 marijuana seedlings, and 20 kg 
of marijuana seeds following a raid on a four-hectare marijuana 
plantation in the mountains of Maimbung, Sulu. Maimbung is one 
of the many areas in Sulu considered to be a Moro National 
Liberation Front stronghold. (Manila PHILIPPINE DAILY INQUIRER 
in English 23 May 94 p 15) 
<H5>  Thailand </H5>
<H5>  Two Arrested in Chiang Rai With 4.5 Kg of Heroin </H5>
  Narcotics officers arrested Sawang Wongyai, 36, and Santi 
Kattiyasarn, 34, at the Chiang Rai bus terminal on 19 May. They 
had 12 packs of heroin weighing 4.5 kg hidden inside of a 
suitcase. (Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 24 May 94 p 6) 

</TEXT>

