<F P=100> EAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> LAOS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Souban Launches `Overall' Drug Suppression Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Souban Launches `Overall' Drug Suppression Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2805114394 Vientiane Vitthayou Hengsat Radio Network in 
Lao 0000 GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2805114394 </F>
<F P=104>  Vientiane Vitthayou Hengsat Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Lao </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Narcotic drugs pose a serious threat to mankind at 
present. The use of and the trafficking in drugs have become 
widespread, thus causing extremely adverse effects on many 
countries around the world. Therefore, the issue of narcotic 
drugs has now become a problem which must be tackled by all 
countries. 
  The above-mentioned statement was made by Souban 
Salitthilat, 
deputy foreign affairs minister and chairman of the Lao National 
Committee for the Control and Suppression of Narcotic Drugs, at 
the opening of a meeting to launch an overall plan for 
controlling and suppressing narcotic drugs until the year 2000. 
The meeting was held in Vientiane early this week and attended 
by drug control and suppression representatives from ten 
northern provinces. In his statement, Souban Salitthilat also 
said: To achieve better results in suppressing narcotic drugs, 
cooperation and coordination must be earnestly established 
between the drug producing and using countries. If the user 
countries only blame the producer countries, mutual suspicion 
will be further deepened and cooperation will become designed 
for unilateral interests only. The minister stressed that Laos 
is ready to cooperate with all countries and international 
organizations in solving this problem with its own ability and 
on the basis of mutual respect for each other's independence, 
sovereignty, and territorial integrity, and mutual benefit. 
  The chairman of the Lao National Committee for the Control 
and Suppression of Narcotic Drugs stressed that on the basis of 
the aforementioned principle, the Lao Government, with 
cooperation from the UN Commission on Narcotic Drugs, has mapped 
out an overall plan on suppressing narcotic drugs until the year 
2000. This plan spells out urgent requirements, strategy, and 
policy for practical implementation. The plan consists of 16 
projects, requiring a budget of U.S. $35 million to implement. 
The long-term objectives of the plan are aimed at gradually 
reducing the planting of poppy crops, doing away with the 
planting of marijuana for commercial purposes, decreasing and 
controlling the needs [of consumption] of narcotic drug users, 
suppressing drug trafficking and production as well as any 
illegal acts committed in violation of narcotics suppression 
laws, controlling any legal activity on the use of drugs, and 
providing convenience and cooperation to the international 
organizations. 
  The Lao Government has paid close attention to enforcing our 
narcotics suppression laws to suppress trafficking by 
establishing a narcotics control and suppression organization 
staffed with more than 20 police officers to carry out drug 
suppression drives in cooperation with local police, Customs, 
and postal authorities. 
  The Lao National Committee for the Control and Suppression 
of 
Narcotic Drugs was formed in 1990 under the chairmanship of 
Souban and is composed of members from various state agencies, 
namely the Ministry of Interior, the Ministry of Finance, the 
Customs Department, the Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry, 
the Public Health Ministry, the Justice Ministry, the Education 
Ministry, and the Prime Minister's Office. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

