<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> KAZAKHSTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN To Grant Country Funds for Antidrug Efforts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN To Grant Country Funds for Antidrug Efforts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2805223594 Almaty Kazakh Radio Network in Kazakh 1400 GMT 
28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2805223594 </F>
<F P=104>  Almaty Kazakh Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Kazakh </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A press-conference on drug smuggling issues has been 
held at the Internal Affairs Ministry. It was attended by 
Giorgio Giacomelli, the UN deputy secretary general and 
executive director of the UN's fund for drug abuse. His visit 
to Kazakhstan could be explained by a tendency for establishing 
relations between Kazakhstan's drug dealers and that of the CIS 
and foreign countries. Last year 197 foreigners were detained 
for illegal drug dealing in Kazakhstan. Internal Affairs 
Minister Vladimir Shumov said that Kazakhstan has the material 
that is needed for illegal production of hashish type drugs. We 
are worried about the substantial increase in influx of Opium 
type drugs to Kazakhstan from Russia, Ukraine, Tajikistan, 
Turkmenistan, and Uzbekistan. The fact that two-thirds of drug 
addicts are young people in their 20's is also of great concern. 
This is the reason why we decided to take tougher steps in 
combatting it. 
  Giacomelli noted that it is impossible to combat drug 
smuggling single-handed. Therefore, the United Nations puts 
forward its own comprehensive program aimed at stopping drug 
trafficking. The United Nations' goal is to join the efforts of 
different countries in addressing these problems. Conditions 
should be created that will make drug cultivation unprofitable. 
With this aim in mind relevant international trade legislation 
has to be adopted. Touching upon the subject of UN assistance to 
Kazakhstan, Giacomelli said that this will depend on a number of 
things. The United Nations intends to grant Kazakhstan $0.5 
million under this program. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

