<H3> <TI>   PGR Conducts Operation at Juarez Exits To `Trap' Members of </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PGR Conducts Operation at Juarez Exits To `Trap' Members of </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Arellano   Felix Group 

<F P=102> 94WB0042A Mexico City EXCELSIOR in Spanish 12 May 94 STATES 
Section p 2 </F>

<F P=103> 94WB0042A </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City EXCELSIOR </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Manuel Cabrera] </F>
  [Text] Ciudad Juarez, Chihuahua, 11 May--Agents from the 
Attorney General's Office (PGR) mounted an operation here today 
(from 1630 to 1930) at the exits of the international bridges 
crossing to the United States. Its purpose was to trap the 
members of the Arellano Felix family and its accomplices, 
according to the Federal Judicial Police (PJF) first commander 
in the state, Javier Norona Guerrero. 
  He added that the operation was conducted on the export 
lanes 
by 100 Federal Judicial agents who, besides seeking "escapees," 
were also looking for possible drug shipments on those bridges. 
  Norona Guerrero claimed that the instructions from the PJF 
director, Adrian Carrera Fuentes, who visited Nuevo Laredo and 
Matamoros, Tamaulipas, today, are to continue the search for the 
Arellano Felix brothers and Juan Garcia Abrego. The latter 
apparently was here a few days ago. 
  He noted that the thorough inspections of departing vehicles 
were made strategically. The sides of the lanes were blocked by 
a group of Judicial Police agents armed with "banana clip" 
weapons, while others requested identifications and searched 
automobile trunks. 
  Although Carrera Fuentes left this town today, a PGR group 
led by Commander Jose Luis Patino is reinforcing the search for 
Garcia Abrego and the Arellano Felix group in the Casas Grandes 
region. 
  As for a possible "tipoff" to the fugitives, Norona Guerrero 
explained that there was none, because the measure is part of 
the permanent campaign to find the aforementioned drug 
traffickers. 
  Before leaving Ciudad Juarez, Adrian Carrera announced that 
a 
security corridor had been formed from Tijuana to Matamoros, to 
prevent the Arellano Felix group and Garcia Abrego from leaving 
Mexico. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

