<H3> <TI>   `Interdisciplinary' Antidrug Police Units Planned for Baja </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Interdisciplinary' Antidrug Police Units Planned for Baja </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
California 

<F P=102>   94WB0042E Mexico City EXCELSIOR in Spanish 12 May 94 pp 1-A, 
10-A </F>

<F P=103> 94WB0042E </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City EXCELSIOR </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Salvador Martinez G.] </F>
  [Excerpts] Avoiding the promotion of attitudes leading to 
confusion in the society, refraining from disinformation and 
rumor, and adhering strictly to the law, with full respect for 
the separation of powers: these policies were proclaimed 
yesterday by President Salinas de Gortari and Baja California 
Governor Ernesto Ruffo Appel, during a long conversation held at 
Los Pinos. 
  Salinas de Gortari and Ruffo Appel, with the mayor of 
Tijuana, Hector Osuna Jaime, agreed in citing the undeferrable 
need to pool efforts throughout the republic. They made a series 
of commitments aimed at coordinating efforts to deal with the 
common enemy of Mexico and Baja California: the drug traffic. 
  The Baja California governor, who recently expressed his 
disapproval of the manner in which that state's deputy attorney 
general, Sergio Ortiz Lara, was arrested by Federal Judicial 
Police personnel, arrived at Los Pinos shortly after noon. 
[passage omitted] 
  The heads of the three government echelons--federal, state, 
and municipal--agreed, with respect to public security, on the 
creation of interdisciplinary police units, with federal, state, 
and municipal forces. Their main objective will be to combat 
activities and crimes associated with drug trafficking. 
  It was explained that these units will engage in preventive 
and surveillance activity, through close cooperation in their 
operations. These police units will have agents from the Federal 
and State Public Prosecutors' Offices present to assist them. 
The latter will submit joint reports to the authorities on the 
three government levels, under the political responsibility of 
the federal chief executive, the state governor, and the mayor 
of Tijuana, in their respective jurisdictions. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

