<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Felix Gallardo Given 40-Year Sentence </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Felix Gallardo Given 40-Year Sentence </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94WB0041D Mexico City EXCELSIOR in Spanish 11 May 94 pp 5-A, 
22-A </F>

<F P=103> 94WB0041D </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City EXCELSIOR </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Hector Adorno Ruiz] </F>
  [Excerpts] The "capo" of the drug traffic in Mexico, Miguel 
Angel Felix Gallardo, was found guilty of the murders of DEA 
[Drug Enforcement Administration] agent Enrique Camarena Salazar 
and the Mexican pilot, Alfredo Zavala Avelar, of crimes against 
health in the form of cocaine trafficking, and of illegal 
deprivation of freedom. He was sentenced to the maximum term of 
40 years in prison by the fourth district judge of criminal 
proceedings of the National Supreme Court, assigned to 
Guadalajara, Jalisco. 
  In his decision, the administrator of justice in the federal 
jurisdiction found Miguel Angel Felix Gallardo to have acted 
with the aggravating circumstances of premeditation and 
advantage in the kidnapping and murder of the DEA agent, 
Camarena Salazar, and the Mexican aviator-pilot, Alfredo Zavala 
Avelar. 
  At the conclusion of the criminal proceedings lasting nine 
years, the federal judge also found the implicated subject, 
considered the "czar of cocaine in Mexico" and the "drug traffic 
`capo' in Mexico" before his arrest in April 1989, guilty of 
crimes against health. The latter were in the forms of 
clandestine entry, illegal export, collection, purchase and 
sale, and storage of large amounts of cocaine. Hence, he decided 
to impose the maximum penalty stipulated in the Federal Code of 
Criminal Procedures at the time that the federal social 
representative brought penal action against him. 
  Miguel Angel Felix Gallardo was informed of the sentence 
associated with proceedings 82/85 inside the Federal Maximum 
Security Center where he has been confined since 1992. He was 
transferred there from the Southern Crime Prevention Prison, 
where he had been held since 1989, following his arrest at a 
residence in the Chapalita subdivision of Guadalajara, Jalisco. 
  The notification procedure was carried out based on letters 
requisitorial from the Jalisco federal judge sent to his 
counterpart in Mexico State, so that the hearing might be 
established and held in the federal maximum security prison. 
[passage omitted] 
  If the sentence should be appealed, the trial against the 
implicated subject will be continued in the pertinent court with 
several judges, and the magistrates who are members of that body 
will be the ones to issue the pertinent decision, with which 
both parties may also express dissent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

