<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> PARAGUAY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Congress Approves Agreement With U.S. on Money Laundering </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Congress Approves Agreement With U.S. on Money Laundering </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1006164394 Asuncion NOTICIAS in Spanish 10 Jun 94 p 12 </F>
<F P=103> PY1006164394 </F>
<F P=104>  Asuncion NOTICIAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Chamber of Deputies on 9 June passed a draft 
bill approving an agreement to cooperate in the prevention and 
control of the laundering of money derived from the illegal 
trade of drugs and narcotics. The document was signed between 
the Paraguayan and U.S. Governments in November 1993. 
  Deputy Constantino Mencia Ayala, head of the Drug 
Enforcement 
Committee, argued in favor of approving the bill considering the 
need for mutual cooperation to control drug traffickers' 
international money laundering. 
  He said the agreement's purpose was to eradicate money 
laundering through adequate cooperation between the two 
governments, particularly considering the major increase in 
mafia-linked financial operations to launder dollars obtained 
through the sale of narcotics. 
  Deputies passed the bill by a broad margin and immediately 
sent it to the executive branch for promulgation. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

