<H3> <TI>   Air Force Commander's Resignation, U.S. Radar Decision in </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Air Force Commander's Resignation, U.S. Radar Decision in </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
`No   Way Connected' 

<F P=102> PY0606164794 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1604 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0606164794 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 6 Jun (EFE) -- Peruvian Air Force (FAP) 
commander General Jose Nadal Paiva has resigned suddenly. 
General Enrique Astete replaced him as the FAP commander today. 
  Nadal submitted his resignation just as the U.S. Government 
halted the supply of radar obtained information to the FAP for 
use in the struggle against drug trafficking. According to 
military sources, the two are in no way connected. 
  The same sources stated that the Air Force commander 
resigned 
for "very personal reasons." Other sources stated that he 
resigned for health reasons. 
  Nadal Paiva should have retired, due to his age, in 1993 but 
continued following a decision by Peruvian President Alberto 
Fujimori, who is also commander in chief of the Armed Forces by 
a mandate of the Constitution. 
  The new FAP commander was the Air Force chief of staff and 
prior to that director of military operations and attache at the 
Peruvian Embassy in the United States. 

</TEXT>

