<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chirac Discusses Narcotics Problem, Other Issues With </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chirac Discusses Narcotics Problem, Other Issues With </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
President   Clinton 

<F P=102> BR0806122494 Paris LE FIGARO in French 8 Jun 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> BR0806122494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE FIGARO </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Francoise Varenne report: "Clinton-Chirac Discussions"] </F>
  [Text] Jacques Chirac [Paris mayor and Rally for the 
Republic president] yesterday met with U.S. President Bill 
Clinton. The half-hour meeting took place in U.S. Ambassador 
Pamela Harriman's residence in the rue du Faubourg St. Honore. 
The mayor of Paris was accompanied by Didier Quentin, the 
town's international relations director, and Pierre Lellouche, 
his foreign policy and defense adviser. Bill Clinton's 
entourage included U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher 
and Thomas McLarty, chief of the presidential staff. Jacques 
Chirac and Bill Clinton spent most of the meeting discussing 
international affairs, and in particular the Bosnian conflict. 
On this issue, they were agreed that the arms embargo should 
not be lifted. The RPR president also insisted on the 
seriousness of the situation in Algeria, which risks 
destabilizing the whole Maghreb region. Where nuclear testing 
is concerned, Jacques Chirac stressed the need for France to 
carry out a few more tests before switching over to test 
simulations. For his part, Bill Clinton expressed his concern 
about the growing risk of the proliferation of weapons of mass 
destruction (nuclear, chemical, and bacteriological) and the 
danger that this represents, insofar as they could be used by 
terrorist groups. 
<H5>  Working Group </H5>
  Moreover, Jacques Chirac explained at length to the U.S. 
President his views on the urgent and vital need to attack the 
narcotics problem at the production stage. In particular, he 
stressed the considerable increase in the production of heroin 
and its consequences, especially for young people. 
  The former French prime minister also underscored the need 
to 
define a policy and take action, possibly under the aegis of the 
United Nations, to encourage countries producing narcotics to 
think about promoting alternative sources of revenue for their 
farmers. 
  President Clinton showed much interest in this proposal. The 
two men decided that regular contacts would be established 
between experts on both sides and that a working group would be 
set up to define a policy for the fight against narcotics 
production. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

