<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> KAZAKHSTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Operation To Destroy Illegal Drug Crops Launched </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Operation To Destroy Illegal Drug Crops Launched </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906101594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0924 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0906101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Akimov] </F>
  [Text] Alma Ata [Almaty] June 9 TASS -- A large-scale 
operation to spot and destroy illegally planted crops of 
narcotic plants was launched in Kazakhstan. The operation, to 
last till November 30, involves thousands of staffers of the 
interior minister in virtually all regions of the country. 
  Special attention is given to putting a stop to the delivery 
of the narcotics from the Chuya Valley. According to the 
information published in the latest issue of the Kazakhstan 
weekly PANORAMA with a reference to an official of the 
Kazakhstan Interior Ministry, about 5,000 tonnes of marijuana is 
manufactured every year out of hemp grown in the Chuya valley. 
These narcotics then spread all over the world via Russia and 
Kazakhstan's southern borders. In addition, Kazakhstan was 
being turned of late into a link for narcotics traffic via China 
from the so-called golden triangle to Europe. 
  Kazakhstan law enforcement bodies expect the hunting of 
narcotics producers and narcotics dealers to be effective. Some 
850 illegally planted plots of narcotic crops have been found 
and destroyed during such operations last year. Over 27 tonnes 
of marijuana and 16.5 tonnes of poppy straw were prevented from 
entering trafficking. Also some 12 tonnes of narcotics were 
apprehended. Their total value at black market prices of the 
Kazakh capital make up about 6.3 million U.S. dollars. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

