<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> UKRAINE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Ministry Research Indicates Drug Trafficking </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interior Ministry Research Indicates Drug Trafficking </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
`Increasingly   Widespread' 

<F P=102> PM0706105394 Moscow NOVAYA YEZHEDNEVNAYA GAZETA in Russian 4 
Jun 94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PM0706105394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NOVAYA YEZHEDNEVNAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yuriy Kirillov under the "Crime" rubric: "The </F>
`Carpathian Poppy' Is in Full Flower"] 
  [Text] Drug abuse and illegal drug trafficking are 
becoming increasingly widespread in Ukraine. Special research 
conducted by the Ministry of Internal Affairs shows that there 
are now approximately 400,000 users of narcotics in the state. 
  Over the past year staffers of the West Ukrainian Internal 
Affairs Transport Administration alone, who serve the Lvov 
Railroad, have exposed 874 cases of the acquisition, keeping, 
and transportation of narcotics and have instituted criminal 
proceedings against 656 people and administrative proceedings 
against 160. Of the 7.5 tonnes of raw drugs confiscated on 
Ukraine's railroads, the Lvov main line has accounted for almost 
three tonnes. Operational workers have established 30 sources 
of drug sales. 
  More than one tonne of poppy straw has already been 
confiscated in 1994, and many possessors of raw drugs have been 
exposed and arrested. "Carpathian poppies" are brought mainly 
into Ukraine's Dnepropetrovsk, Donetsk, Kherson, Nikolayev, and 
Lugansk Oblasts and also into the Caucasus. 
  Great anxiety is occasioned by the fact that drug dealers 
have started working according to the "team method." More than 
70 such groups have already been arrested. The 
arrestees--mainly unemployed young people under the age of 
35--include over 100 with previous convictions and also 92 who 
are citizens of other states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

