<H3> <TI>   Counternarcotics Chiefs Agree To Create New Organization To </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Counternarcotics Chiefs Agree To Create New Organization To </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Fight   Drug Trafficking 

<F P=102> PA0606221394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network in Spanish 1800 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0606221394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Cripton Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Latin American narcotics chiefs agreed to create an 
organization to fight the scourge of drug trafficking, which is 
increasingly more interconnected with another illegal business: 
gunrunning from Europe to Latin America. The decision was 
adopted at a meeting in the Dominican Republic. Here is a 
report by Chelo Garcia: [begin recording] 
  Garcia: There is concern that the ties between 
Latin American drug traffickers and gunrunners are increasingly 
getting closer. They work in teams and support each other. 
Sophisticated long- and short-range weapons of every caliber, 
mostly from Europe, are flooding the Latin American black 
markets. The narcotics chiefs of Latin America decided to make 
efforts to break this deadly alliance during the drug summit 
held in the Dominican Republic. 
  Colombian counternarcotics chief Colonel Leonardo 
Gallego: The most important things were the plans for new 
methods and means to strengthen this struggle against drug 
trafficking. 
  Garcia: It was also proposed at the drug summit 
that the Latin American countries form a single bloc of support 
to control drug cultivation, production, processing, and 
trafficking. They will also work shoulder to shoulder to 
prevent the use of aircraft, vessels, and ground transportation 
to supply materials that Latin American drug traffickers need to 
produce drugs. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

