<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> BOLIVIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Some Coca Growers Express Willingness To Replace Coca for </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Some Coca Growers Express Willingness To Replace Coca for </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Other   Products 

<F P=102> PY1706174594 Cochabamba LOS TIEMPOS in Spanish 8 Jun 94 p A6 </F>
<F P=103> PY1706174594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cochabamba LOS TIEMPOS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] La Paz, 7 Jun (LOS TIEMPOS) -- Approximately 
20,000 peasants--some 20 percent of the coca growers of the 
Cochabamba tropical region and La Paz department--today 
expressed their willingness "to replace coca with other 
products" on condition the government carries out, in the 
short-term, "effective alternative development plans" in the 
production zones. 
  Several coca growers leaders told LOS TIEMPOS that their 
unions "will do this if the Government Ministry and the Social 
Defense Secretariat" fulfill their commitments with the peasants. 
  The union leader said: "They just make promises but have 
done 
nothing to carry out the projects and works established in the 
agreements and documents signed with officials in March and May 
of this year." [passage omitted] 
  The government announced recently that at least $600 million 
has been invested in alternative development plans in the 
Chapare region of Cochabamba and the Yungas region of La Paz. 
  The official spokesmen added that only about 10 percent [as 
published] of that amount--about $100 million--has "really" been 
used in projects to replace coca. 
  The coca leaders added that most of the plans "failed, to 
the 
misfortune of the peasants and the country." 

</TEXT>

