<DATE1>  13 June 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> BRAZIL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Country Reportedly Becoming Main Cocaine `Warehouse' For </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Country Reportedly Becoming Main Cocaine `Warehouse' For </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
U.S.,   Europe 

<F P=102> PY1406193994 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 
13 Jun 94 p 10 </F>

<F P=103> PY1406193994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Ascanio Seleme] </F>
  [Text] Brasilia -- Brazil has become the main warehouse for 
the cocaine that is consumed in the United States and Europe. 
Last week's record seizure of 7.5 metric tons of cocaine 
dispelled any remaining doubts about the key role the country 
plays in shipping the cocaine that is produced in Colombia, 
Bolivia, and Peru. In addition to distributing drugs to other 
countries, for the past four years Brazil has featured a new 
aspect in its trafficking activities that concerns police 
authorities: Brazil is producing cocaine. 
  The Federal Police [PF] believe at least two percent of 
Colombian-owned refining laboratories have been operating in 
Brazilian territory since 1990. 
  Sergio Sakon, chief of the PF Narcotics Enforcement 
Department, rules out the possibility that this percentage will 
increase in the next few years. In addition to difficulties in 
transporting the cocaine base--a coca byproduct--into Brazil, 
there are no experts in cocaine refining in the country. 
Brazilian laboratories are operated by Colombian and Bolivian 
"cooks," who attract attention in border areas and thus increase 
the risk of a police crackdown. 
  Sakon added: Furthermore, laboratories require the 
cooperation of their host communities. They can get this 
cooperation in Colombia, but not in Brazil. 
  Studies by the DEA (the U.S. drug enforcement organization) 
show, however, that U.S. military actions against the Colombian 
cartels have resulted in the laboratories being moved to safer 
ground, mainly to the Brazilian border with Colombia, Bolivia, 
and Peru. The region of Brazilian that houses the laboratories 
is identical to the areas where the main cocaine refining 
laboratories are located in the three neighboring countries: 
Tropical forest and savannas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

