<F P=101> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Record Hashish Haul From Seizure in al-Biqa' Valley </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Record Hashish Haul From Seizure in al-Biqa' Valley </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Incinerated 

<F P=102>   NC1606131994 Paris AFP in English 1245 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1606131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>
BFN 

  [Text] Al-'Amrusiyah, Lebanon, June 16 (AFP) -- Lebanon 
destroyed on Thursday 31 tonnes of hashish with a street value 
of about 10 million dollars in what officials described as a 
record haul. 
  General Salim Salim, head of the criminal investigation 
department, told reporters the drugs had been mainly destined 
for Holland and were seized in cooperation with Syrian 
authorities last month. 
  "It's a sizeable seizure. The Lebanese authorities should be 
very pleased indeed today," Denis Gray, a police attache at the 
Australian High Commission in Cyprus, told AFP. 
  Gray, who was representing foreign police based in Cyprus, 
witnessed the operation along with officers from the British and 
French embassies in Beirut at the al-'Amrusiyah incinerator 10 
kilometers (six miles) south of Beirut. 
  In addition to the hashish, six kilograms of opium, three 
kilograms of heroin and two kilograms of cocaine also went up in 
smoke. 
  Around 20 people were arrested when the Lebanese Army in 
collaboration with the Syrian intelligence services ventured 
into remote mountainous areas of the al-Hirmil region of the 
Syrian-controlled al-Biqa' Valley. 
  "We ventured into very dangerous territory where we had not 
gone to since the 1920s," said Salim, who personally conducted 
the operations. 
  Huge fortunes from the drug trade were made in the al-Biqa', 
but the government in cooperation with Syrian authorities has 
set fire to poppy and cannabis fields in a ban imposed since the 
civil war ended in 1991. 

</TEXT>

