<H3> <TI>   Council Acts To Prevent Illegal Opium Poppy Growing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Council Acts To Prevent Illegal Opium Poppy Growing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1606181094 Sofia BTA in English 1638 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1606181094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, June 16 (BTA) -- The National Council for 
Combatting Drug Abuse and Trafficking today approved a report of 
the Organized Crime Control Service and the National Narcotics 
Service (with the Ministry of Health Care) on an inquiry 
conducted in the region of Sandanski, Petrich and Melnik 
(southwestern Bulgaria) into illegal cultivation of opium poppy, 
BTA learnt from the Press Office of the Council of Ministers. 
  The Ministry of Agriculture has been assigned to draft a 
programme for restricting opium plantations by the end of 
September 1994. The council appointed a working group for 
updating the legislative basis on control over narcotic 
substances production, circulation and use, including on 
tightening control over poppy cultures. Mr. Pavlin Nedelchev, 
deputy justice minister, was appointed head of the working group. 
  The National Council decided to update the prices of 
narcotic 
substances subject to illegal trafficking to be used for the 
needs of the investigation, the court and the prosecution. 

</TEXT>

