<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> BOLIVIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sanchez, Cardenas Deny `Secret' Agreement Between MNR, MIR </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sanchez, Cardenas Deny `Secret' Agreement Between MNR, MIR </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2206032694 La Paz PRESENCIA in Spanish 12 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PY2206032694 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz PRESENCIA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santa Cruz, 11 Jun (PRESENCIA) -- Acting President 
Victor Hugo Cardenas said today that the country does not need 
any kind of political deal or secret "agreement," as he would be 
the first to report such cases. 
  Cardenas made this comment in reference to reports about a 
tacit agreement between the MIR [Movement of the Revolutionary 
Left] and the MNR [Nationalist Revolutionary Movement] by which 
no charges would be filed against national MIR leaders for their 
links with drug trafficking, in exchange for a harsh sentence 
for Justices Edgar Oblitas Fernandez and Ernesto Poppe Zubieta. 
  Cardenas rejected the validity of that report, saying that 
there are no real elements to sustain the media reports of a 
"dubious political scheme" between the MNR and the MIR regarding 
the two issues. Cardenas asserted that the government wants to 
do justice and not break it. 
  He said, however, that if a situation such as that reported 
by the media emerges, "I would be the first to report it and 
condemn it, as this type of agreement or deal can only hurt the 
country and the democratic process that was so hard for the 
country to recover." 
  President Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada himself categorically 
denied the media report before leaving for Colombia and the 
United States, saying that "our struggle is against corruption. 
We don't negotiate these cases, and although we don't want to 
hurt anyone, our will is to enforce the law." 

</TEXT>

