<H3> <TI>   Vice President-Elect Vows New Administration To </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vice President-Elect Vows New Administration To </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
`Relentlessly'   Fight Drugs 

<F P=102> PA2506021794 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2506021794 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Raul Gutierrez; from the "24 Hours Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] President-elect Ernesto Samper has asked THE MIAMI 
HERALD to correct its position, and President Cesar Gaviria 
expressed his support for the president-elect. [begin recording] 
  Gutierrez: For the first time, President Gaviria 
talked about the attempt to infuse the presidential campaigns 
with drug trafficking money, as detailed by the recordings he 
received from Andres Pastrana four days prior to the elections. 
  Gaviria: All Colombians want a thorough 
investigation to yield results soon in order to dispel doubts. 
  Gutierrez: President Gaviria expressed support for 
the president-elect, who announced that, should he find out that 
any member of his team is involved, he would dismiss him from 
any post he might occupy in the government. 
  Meanwhile, Vice President-elect Humberto De la Calle, who is 
a member of the Promoters Committee for the Penalization of Drug 
Consumption, said the new administration will relentlessly fight 
drug traffickers. 
  De la Calle: First, we will continue the military 
and police fight against drug traffickers. 
  Gutierrez: There will also be new laws to penalize 
money laundering and appropriations. [end recording] 
  [Madrid EFE in Spanish at 0059 on 25 June transmits a 
175-word Santa Fe de Bogota-datelined report citing De la Calle 
as saying: "It will become a fight to arrest and make drug 
traffickers pay the debts they owe to Colombian society." The 
report adds: "The new government will submit two bills to 
increase drug traffickers' prison terms by means of a reform of 
the Penal Code, thereby closing the gap on `certain legal limbos 
and loose interpretations' that let criminals enjoy prison terms 
shorter than the ones they deserve. De la Calle also pointed 
out that the new administration will make money `laundering' a 
crime in Colombia and will seek international cooperation to 
trace the routes travelled by illegal money."] 

</TEXT>

