<F P=101> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   INCD Director Comments on Antidrug Operation in Sinaloa, </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    INCD Director Comments on Antidrug Operation in Sinaloa, </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Durango,   Chihuahua 

<F P=102> PA2406034594 Mexico City LA JORNADA in Spanish 21 Jun 94 p 37 </F>
<F P=103> PA2406034594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City LA JORNADA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Antonio Quevedo Susunaga] </F>
  [Text] Culiacan, Sinaloa, 20 Jun -- Virgilio de la Fuente 
Ruiz, director of the National Counternarcotics Institute 
(INCD), has reported that an operation involving 41 federal 
agents was implemented today in the mountainous areas of the 
States of Sinaloa, Durango, and Chiahuahua to intensify the 
struggle against drug trafficking. 
  He also said the INCD has eight agents highly qualified in 
the area of investigation, who will work full-time to determine 
the activities, whereabouts, and money laundering activities of 
Sinaloa's most important drug traffickers and drug producers. 
The official said that the 41 federal agents are part of a 
select group of investigators, adding that they were taken in 
helicopters to bases the Attorney General's Office (PGR) has set 
up in mountainous areas. 
  The official stressed that authorities will investigate 
those 
who finance the production of narcotics, because the aim is to 
specifically punish those who provide the financial resources, 
not so much drug couriers. The INCD director asserted that 
authorities have detected some marijuana and poppy plantations 
in the mountains dividing Durango, Chihuahua, and Sonora. 
  Meanwhile, Antonio Figueroa Lee, president of the Alberto 
Sanchez Gonzalez Bar Association, affirmed that the PGR must 
improve the process of selecting agents to effectively fight 
drug trafficking. 

</TEXT>

