<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   INCD Commissioner Comments on Training of PGR Personnel at </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    INCD Commissioner Comments on Training of PGR Personnel at </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
FBI   Academy 

<F P=102> PA2006002494 Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 13 Jun 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> PA2006002494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City UNOMASUNO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

  [Text] With the conviction that drug trafficking is a 
worldwide problem that should be attacked jointly, the Mexican 
state has called for the establishment of a common front to 
combat this activity, because drug trafficking needs to be 
combated with great efforts and increasingly larger economic and 
human resources, the Attorney General's Office (PGR) has stated. 
  Thus, Mexico and the United States must continue to support 
joint strategies without violating the sovereignty of either 
country to combat drug trafficking. 
  During the inauguration of a training course for PGR agents, 
at installations of the FBI Academy in Virginia, the United 
States, Rene Paz Horta, National Counternarcotics Institute 
(INCD) commissioner, said the intensification of efforts and the 
support of other nations strengthen the task of combating drug 
trafficking and related crimes, which he described as "among the 
most serious scourges of humanity." 
  Representing Attorney General Humberto Benitez Trevino, who 
is responsible for counternarcotics efforts in the country, Paz 
said the training of PGR agents will help find solutions to this 
problem and reflects the two countries' willingness to cooperate. 
  During the ceremony to inaugurate courses for PGR agents at 
the FBI Academy in Quantico, Virginia, Paz said Mexico and the 
United States must continue to promote joint strategies, without 
violating the sovereignty of either nation, to fight drug 
trafficking. 
  The INCD commissioner said there is a firm conviction that 
drug trafficking is a worldwide problem that must be confronted 
jointly. He added this experience reinforces the hope of 
establishing a united front to combat this type of crime while 
respecting each other, their ethical values, and the law. 
  He added the Mexican state headed by President Carlos 
Salinas 
de Gortari has promoted the establishment of a common front 
against crime, because the antidrug fight requires tremendous 
efforts and increasingly larger economic and human resources. 
  Paz said it is painful to see thousands of human beings, 
particularly young ones, fall victim to drugs. He highlighted 
the need to expand rehabilitation programs for adults as well as 
the people's participation in preventive efforts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

