<F P=101> PAKISTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tribals Threaten To Resume Poppy Cultivation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tribals Threaten To Resume Poppy Cultivation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2106005494 Islamabad PAKISTAN in Urdu 20 Jun 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> BK2106005494 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PAKISTAN </F>
<F P=105>  Urdu </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Peshawar -- After a break of three weeks, local 
people have again started holding protest demonstrations in the 
Tirah area of Khyber Agency. The demonstrations are being held 
against the presence of militia forces which have been stationed 
in the area for the last two years. A large protest rally was 
held yesterday with hundreds of tribals holding black flags and 
chanting slogans against the government and the administration. 
The demonstrators say that the presence of the militia has 
affected their lives and, therefore, they should leave the area. 
The demonstrators warned that the situation might become worse 
if the militia is not called off from the area within two 
months. The demonstrators claimed that the government promised 
to give them attractive incentives for alternative crops to 
poppy cultivation. But it has failed to fulfill that promise so 
far they claimed and threatened to resume poppy cultivation on a 
large-scale if incentives are not offered by September 1994. 

</TEXT>

