<H3> <TI>   Government Reports Increase in Number of Drug Addicts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Reports Increase in Number of Drug Addicts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2106092194 Hamburg WELT AM SONNTAG in German 19 Jun 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU2106092194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg WELT AM SONNTAG </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Heinz Vielain: "Number of First Drugs Consumers </F>
Increases By 20 Percent"] 
  [Text] Bonn -- The number of narcotics addicts in Germany 
is growing, the Federal Government reports. The number of first 
consumers of drugs increased to 4,538 between January and May. 
That is 20.4 percent up on the same period last year. 
  The government's drug expert, State Secretary Eduard 
Lintner, 
told WELT AM SONNTAG that in the first five months of 1994, 643 
people were killed by drugs. He warned against "misinterpreting 
the Karlsruhe ruling on liberalizing small amounts of drugs for 
personal use." 
  Lintner fears that "the danger of a clear increase in 
consumption will be played down if prosecution is predictable." 
From the beginning of January to the end of May, 566 kg of 
heroin were seized in Germany. In addition, authorities seized 
246 kg of cocaine, 1,540 kg of cannabis, 125 kg of marijuana, 45 
kg of amphetamines, and 7,121 LSD doses. 
  Asked about the ongoing discussion about small amounts of 
hashish or marijuana for personal consumption going unpunished, 
the drugs expert said: "Guidelines that clearly determine small 
amounts in absolute figures lead to prosecutions also being 
predictable for dealers and their instigators." Dealers could 
disguise themselves as consumers of small amounts. That way 
they could easily evade the police. 
  Since North Rhine-Westphalia's SPD [Social Democratic Party] 
government decided in May to liberalize the possession of small 
amounts of heroin, cocaine, and other narcotics, Federal Health 
Minister Seehofer (Christian Democratic Union--CDU) has examined 
whether the narcotics law needs to be amended. An additional 
struggle among the parties can be expected, because Frankfurt's 
SPD Mayor Andreas von Schoeler wants to have the courts 
decontrol the possession of heroin for heavy addicts. 
  On the activities in Frankfurt, which is governed by a 
red-green alliance, the parliamentary manager of the CDU/CSU 
[Christian Social Union], Juergen Ruettgers, told WELT AM 
SONNTAG: "Liberalization of heroin means giving the go-ahead for 
the drugs mafia in Frankfurt; with Frankfurt a city that has 
almost 10,000 drug addicts, of whom some 5,000 are consumers of 
hard drugs. With 146,000 criminal offenses a year, Frankfurt is 
a stronghold of crime in Germany." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

